/PG76/XX/PR

/KAINTERPRETIVE VERSION/XX/PR

We acknowledge as true and trustworthy that there is but one
universal God, and that to Godòs service Israel stands eternally
committed./PR

/PR

We recognize in God the power that has enabled us to triumph
over defeat, persecution and oppression./PR

/PR

It was God who redeemed us from Egyptian bondage, and
delivered us from the despotism of the pharaohs./PR

/PR

For God wills that we be free to use our powers in holy service,
and be not bound to the arbitrary rule of any mortal./PR

/PR

Whenever human rulers usurp divine authority, and exploit the
people, those tyrantsò hearts are hardened, their own arrogance
writes their doom./PR

/PR

Therefore we will never be discouraged nor dismayed when
unrighteous powers rise up to destroy us./PR

/PR

Though enemy hosts pursue us, we shall remember how our
ancestors were saved at the Sea of Reeds./PR

/PR

We therefore repeat the words of triumph with which they gave
thanks for their deliverance:/PR

1945 Reconstructionist Prayer Book (adapted)/XX/PR

/IT(Congregation sings הכמכ ימ/XX, page 79)/PR

/PR

/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. Two beautiful /ITberah/±ot/XX complete the liturgical framework of
the Shema in the evening service. The first of these is called
/ITGeòulah/XX--"Redemption." Recalling the Exodus from Egypt, it thematically
echoes the third paragraph of the Shema. Moreover, it identifies the sover-
eign God, named in the Shemaòs credo, as the power that freed Israel from
slavery. Its vivid, here-and-now recollection of the escape from Egyptian
bondage invites and challenges Israel to claim the redemption as a personal
experience in each generation and to hear echoes of that ancient triumph
over tyranny in each modern-day struggle for freedom, in every attempt
to move toward the messianic future.    /SC/XXS.S./XX/PR

/PR

/PR

